\marglsxn960\margrsxn960\cols2\colno1\colw5040\colsx240\colsr240\colno2\colw5040
{\pard\sl-376\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li980\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f9\fs20 II. Overview of the Approach}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-128\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-234\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs19 In order to have a scene classi cation as accurate as pos-sible, several methods are used and combined. This choice was made with the assumption that because methods have their best e ciency for di erent classes, combining them should improve the overall accuracy. Results presented in section VI further revealed that this assumption was true. The chosen methods for scene classi cation are Gabor de-scriptors (described in section III), {Centrist} feature vec-tors (described in section IV) and color histogram feature vectors (described in section V). Those three descriptors are very di erent and use complementary information of the images. This is the key that enable an e cient combi-nation of the feature vectors.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-175\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li1120\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f9\fs20 III. Gabor-Gist Descriptor}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-128\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-230\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 Gabor descriptors proved their e ciency as robust tex-ture descriptors. Similarity between low level processing in biological vision and Gabor lter banks was found and proved by Daugman [1]. Thus, Gabor descriptor is the way to make computer "understand" images in the way human brain does it.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-43\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-232\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 The Gabor feature extraction consists of designing a set of Gabor lters in the spatio-frequency domain, and form-ing a bank of lters to be applied to the images in order to transform information from the pixel space into the fea-ture space. In the spatial domain, a 2D Gabor lter is a Gaussian kernel function modulated by a sinusoidal plane wave. The Gabor lters are self-similar: all lters can be generated from one mother wavelet by dilation and rota-tion [2].}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-47\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-223\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 In this study, all the experiments were conducted with single 12 lter Gabor bank, but di erent techniques to pre-process data and reduce dimensionality were used.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-176\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f17\fs20 III.1. Gabor Bank Formation}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-128\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-229\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs19 Gabor descriptor for an image is computed by passing the image through the Gabor lter bank. Gabor lter is a linear band-pass lter whose impulse response is de ned as a Gaussian function modulated with a complex sinusoid. Mathematically, a Gabor lter of a particular orientation and frequency is a sinusoid modulated by a Gaussian:}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-192\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li1540\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f18\fs20 h{(}x; y{) =} s{(}x; y{)}g{(}x; y{)}}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-221\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl226\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f11\fs20 where {s}({x; y}) is a sinusoidal plane and {g}({x; y}) is a 2-D Gaussian. The Gaussian is represented by:}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-152\slmult0\par

