{\pard\plain \li0\sl221\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f8\fs16 Fig. 1. Confusion matrix for Gabor Histogram method 1-Coast; 2-Forest; 3-Highway; 4-Mountain; 5-Tall Building}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-282\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-232\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 A Gabor lter in 2 dimensions can be used to approx-imate the frequency and spatial response of the di erent scene categories. Gabor lters can be viewed as speci c edge detectors, which are able to percept edges of a cer-tain orientation and strength. A lter bank consisting of lters with 3 di erent scales (4, 8 and 16) and 4 orienta-tions (0, 45, 90 and 135 degrees) was considered for feature extraction, giving a total of 12 Gabor lters bank.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-241\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f17\fs20 III.2. Gabor Histogram Approach}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-164\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-232\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs19 The idea of this method is to calculate intensity his-togram for Gabor ltered images. A color image converted into grayscale was split into four horizontal pieces in order to preserve some spatial information and potentially in-crease the classi cation accuracy. Each quarter of an im-age in the training and testing sets was convolved with the lter bank. Intensity histogram was calculated from each piece of the image (32 bin histograms showed similar accu-racy to 64 bins). Thus, the feature vector dimensionality is 1x128. Testing was performed in two ways:}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-89\slmult0\par
{{\listtext\tab}\pard\qj\fi-18\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\faauto\rin0\nooverflow\lin400\itap0 \sl-223\slmult0 {\plain\f11\fs20 Calculating average histogram for each class from training images, and then comparing it with his-tograms of testing images using Euclidian distance, }\par\pard\sl-7\slmult0\par
{\listtext\tab}\pard\qj\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\faauto\rin0\nooverflow\lin200\itap0 \sl-229\slmult0 {\plain\f11\fs20 Using Multilayer Perceptron neural network. }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-85\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-228\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f11\fs19 Both classi cation methods performed similarly with 52% overall accuracy (see gure 1). Note that error rates di er from a category to another category. Because Gabor his-togram approach performed very poorly, it was decided to continue experimenting with other approaches.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-242\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f17\fs20 III.3. Gabor "Manual-Bin" Histogram Approach}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-164\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl252\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs19 As mentioned above, the histogram approach leads to the loss of the spatial information: it only indicates the strength of responses in certain directions and scales. The idea of "manual-bin" histogram approach is to calculate}\par}
}\sect\sbkpage\sectd\pard\plain
