\marglsxn960\margrsxn960\cols2\colno1\colw5040\colsx240\colsr240\colno2\colw5040
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-374\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl221\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f8\fs16 Fig. 2. Avaraged histogram for Coast category with Gabor "manual-bin" histogram approach}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-241\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl226\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f11\fs20 the value for each bin separately and thus save the response spatial information and intensity.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-41\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-231\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 The method was tested using MLP on 150 testing im-ages and performed even worse than previous approach - misclassi cation rate of 51%. Overall histogram dimen-sionality reduction approaches on grayscale images showed unsatisfactory classi cation accuracy, hence it was decided to leave histogram idea and move to Gabor-{Gist} descrip-tor.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-180\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f17\fs20 III.4. Gabor-{Gist} Visual Descriptor}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-94\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f11\fs20 4.1 Image Preprocessing}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-128\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-230\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 Gabor-{Gist} feature extraction was performed on color image in contrast to previous approaches. Gabor lter bank (12 lters) was applied to each color plane of RGB images. For better results, color images were rst pre-processed before being ltered: images were whitened and contrast was adjusted.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-43\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-234\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 The purpose of whitening is removing pairwise, linear correlations, and thus remove noise and "simplify" an im-age. Whitening can be done through designing a lter in the frequency domain that will atten the spectrum of a natural image. Amplitude spectrum of such lter has to rise linearly with frequency, to compensate for the am-plitude spectrum of natural images. This can be done through de ning a grid of frequency coordinates. Because convolution in the space domain is equivalent to multiplica-tion in the frequency domain, whitening can be performed through multiplying the spectrum of the image with the spectrum of the lter and taking the inverse Fast Fourier Transform of the ltered image (see gure 3.b). Contrast normalization is the standard operation to be done after whitening. For this project, normalization was done by dividing the output of the whitening step by the local lu-minance variance [3] [4].}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-193\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f11\fs20 4.2 {Gist} Feature Extraction}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-128\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl238\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs19 In the scope of this project, {Gist} dimensionality was reduced using an averaging over non-overlapping square}\par}
}\column

