{\pard\sl-376\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li2220\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f11\fs20 for each pixel of the image.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-42\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li2220\sl236\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi-199 {\f11\fs20 2. Once the CT values of all pixels of the image have been calculated, the histogram of the CT values is computed using function {CENTRIST4lines.m}. This histogram is the {Centrist} feature vector.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-203\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li1820\sl-233\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f11\fs19 The CT value is calculated as follows: for each pixel, the 8 neighbours are compared to the center pixel value and are assigned value 0 if they are greater than the pixel value, 1 is they are smaller (see gure 6). Concatenating all 8 bits give a binary number with value between 0 and 255. This is the CT value. Figure 7 shows the obtained CT values for two adjacent pixels. It reveals dependencies between CT values: the right neighbour of a pixel for a given 3x3 pixels square will be the left neighbour for the adjacent 3x3 square. Thus if the right neighbour pixel value is greater (for example in gure 7, 37 {>} 36), then the left neighbour will be smaller for the next CT value}\par}
}
{
{\pard\plain \li1820\sl207\slmult1 \ql{\f11\fs20 computation (36 {<} 37).}\par}
}
{
{\pard\plain \li0\sl194\slmult1 \ql{\f8\fs16 1-Coast; 2-Forest; 3-}\par}
}\sect\sbknone
