{\pard\plain \li0\sl230\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f8\fs16 Fig. 7. CT value calculation for 2 adjacent pixels. Red circles reveal dependencies between CT values: because 36 {<} 37 when calculating CT value of green box center pixel, the relation will be 37 {>} 36 when calculating CT value of blue box center pixel}\par}
}\column

{\pard\sl-162\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f17\fs20 IV.2. Parameters}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-146\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-231\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 The {Matlab} function {CTfeatureVector.m} creates the feature vector {Centrist} for all training and testing images and saves data in a {.mat} le. In order to obtain the best performance, di erent parameters have to be tested. The following parameters have been used for the rest of the project since they produced the smallest misclassi cation rate:}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-63\slmult0\par
{{\listtext\tab}\pard\qj\fi-18\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\faauto\rin0\nooverflow\lin400\itap0 \sl-223\slmult0 {\plain\f11\fs20 Downsizing the image to a ratio of 0.125. This reduces the computation time and keeps the relevant informa-tion of the image. }\par\pard\sl-41\slmult0\par
{\listtext\tab}\pard\qj\fi-18\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\faauto\rin0\nooverflow\lin400\itap0 \sl-232\slmult0 {\plain\f11\fs20 Dividing the image into 4 lines seemed to be the most e cient: instead of considering the image as a whole entity, it is divided into 4 lines. The {Centrist} vector is computed for each line and the 4 {Centrist} vec-tors are concatenated to obtain the {Centrist} vector of the image. This enable to keep some of the spa-tial information in the image that can help classifying scenes. }\par\pard\sl-41\slmult0\par
{\listtext\tab}\pard\qj\fi-18\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\faauto\rin0\nooverflow\lin400\itap0 \sl-231\slmult0 {\plain\f11\fs19 Histogram Intersection Method. In order to compare the {Centrist} feature vector of a tested image to the mean of the {Centrist} vectors of images belonging to a given class, the measure of di erence must be calculated. This can be done using the Euclidian dis-tance or the Histogram Intersection Method. The His-togram Intersection Method generated much better classi cation than when using the Euclidian distance. }\par\pard\sl-47\slmult0\par
{\listtext\tab}\pard\qj\fi-18\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\faauto\rin0\nooverflow\lin400\itap0 \sl-226\slmult0 {\plain\f11\fs20 40 bins are used for the histograms. This is the best compromise between the classi cation rate, the com-putation time and the size of the generated {Centrist} feature vector. }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-223\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f17\fs20 IV.3. Results with a Neural Network}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-146\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-227\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs19 When fed into a neural network, the {Centrist} method gives a misclassi cation rate of 14% (see gure 8) which is a correct value for a single classi cation method. Note that even if the overall misclassi cation rates for Gabor-{Gist}}\par}
}\sect\sbkpage\sectd\pard\plain
