\pard\sl-260\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl221\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f8\fs16 Fig. 8. Confusion matrix for CENTRIST features. 1-Coast; 2-Forest; 3-Highway; 4-Mountain; 5-Tall Building}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-278\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-231\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f11\fs19 ( gure 5) and for {Centrist} ( gure 8) are both 14%, the misclassi cation rates vary for each category. This means that the method used will a ect each categorie's misclassi-cation rate. For example the Tall Building category has a misclassi cation rate of 0% with the {Centrist} descriptor and 3.3% with Gabor-{Gist}. At the opposite, the Coast category is much better classi ed if Gabor-{Gist} is used (13.3% instead of 23.3% with {Centrist}).}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-239\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li1460\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f9\fs20 V. Color Histogram}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-160\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-228\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 In scope of scene classi cation problem, color descriptors cannot be considered reliable for the reason that colors are the matter of constant change. The same scene appears in di erent colors depending on the time of the day or the season for example.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-62\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-226\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 A lot of papers still o er color descriptors in the combi-nation of texture descriptors and overall experiments show that such combinations improve the performance of classi-cation.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-61\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-234\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 For this project, a simple color histogram descriptor was implemented. The histogram is computed by counting the number of pixels corresponding to the following colors: red, yellow, green, cyan, blue, magenta, white and black. It is performed rst through converting the image to HSV color space and evaluating each plane in order to determine the number of pixels belonging to each of the selected color categories. The number of black and white pixels are esti-mated through Saturation and Value planes, and the rest of color categories are determined through Hue plane. Ev-ery pixel color category is then normalized by dividing the count of the pixels by the number of pixel in the image. A 8-bin color histogram formats 1x8 feature vector (see gure 9.b).}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-63\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-223\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs19 Classi cation accuracy for color histogram features was evaluated using MLP Neural Network (8 input, 8 hidden, 5 output neurons) using 150 testing images from ve di er-}\par}
}\column

{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-338\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl221\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f8\fs16 Fig. 10. Confusion matrix for Color Histogram features. 1-Coast; 2-Forest; 3-Highway; 4-Mountain; 5-Tall Building}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-264\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-233\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f11\fs19 ent categories of scenes. Classi cation error for color his-togram descriptor is 50%, i.e. half of images were misclassi-ed (see gure 10). Color histogram features performed the worst for Coast category images (only 13% accuracy), the best performance is seen for Forest images (83% accuracy). Experiments proved that color cannot be used as a reliable feature for scene categorization problem, but as mentioned before, our study is concerned with improving classi ca-tion accuracy by adding color features to Gabor-{Gist} and Centrist {features and forming the hybrid feature vector} that is expected to provide the minimum misclassi cation rate.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-219\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li1300\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f9\fs20 VI. Hybrid Descriptors}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-113\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f17\fs20 VI.1. Method 1: Voting Algorithm}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-147\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-232\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 In order to combine the di erent feature vectors, a vot-ing algorithm has been coded in the {Matlab} function votingAlgo{. The le} testVotingAlgoFunction.m {can} be used to test the function using Gabor feature vector, Gabor-{Gist} descriptor and {Centrist} feature vector, and display the output. It can also run the tests several times and give an average performance. For the voting algo-rithm, training images are split randomly into a training}\par}
}\sect\sbkpage\sectd\pard\plain
