{\pard\plain \li0\sl-228\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f11\fs20 and a testing set with a chosen percentage. The results for the voting algorithm were not as good as expected. In-deed, gure 11 shows that a lot of images are misclassi ed, knowing that there should be 15 images classi ed in each category.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-45\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-223\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi101 {\f11\fs19 The following of the paper details the classical classi er, the neural network, that has been trained with the feature vectors in order to solve the scene classi cation problem.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-173\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f17\fs20 VI.2. Method 2: Neural Network}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-128\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-232\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs19 The rst step that needs to be done in order to create the hybrid feature vector is data scaling. Features extracted with each approach have to be equally weighted. Scaling values of vector {b} = [{b}{\fs26 \sub min}{;b}{\fs26 \sub max}] in the range of vector {a} = [{a}{\fs26 \sub min}{;a}{\fs26 \sub max}] values is performed using equation (1).}\par}
}
