{
{\pard\plain \li0\sl220\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f11\fs20 where {x} is the initial value of vector {b} and {y} the rescaled value of {b} in the range of {a}.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-43\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-226\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 Figure 12 shows the e ect of applying equation (1) to Gabor-{Gist} and {Centrist} feature vectors. This will later enable the neural network to take them both into account with same weight.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-281\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-232\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 In previous stages, input matrices for each descrip-tor were built and targets stayed the same for the same dataset. In order to create the hybrid vector of features, all that needs to be done is appending one matrix to another ([features1; features2]) and train the MLP network on the new combined input matrix. The same procedure applies for testing input matrix. In the following sub-sections, di erent combinations of features are analysed and classi-cation accuracy is evaluated.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-178\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl239\slmult1 \ql{\f11\fs20 2.1 Gabor + {Centrist} Hybrid Results}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-128\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl226\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi199 {\f11\fs20 The confusion matrix produced by testing the images based on Gabor-{Gist} and {Centrist} descriptors is shown}\par}
}\column

